VIII. CONCLUSION
We studied both adversarial schemes and countermeasures
for the control center for malicious data attacks. The problem
was divided into two regimes: the strong attack regime, in
which so-called unobservable attacks exist, and the weak attack
regime, in which they do not. The boundary between these
regimes is , the size of the smallest unobservable malicious
data attack, which can be considered a security index for a
power system. We provided a characterization of , which
allows for it to be calculated in a computationally efficient
manner making use of submodular function minimization.
In the weak attack regime, we studied the generalized likelihood
ratio test as a detector for this problem; in particular,
this detector was implemented using convex optimization via
norm regularization. We also provided a residue energy
heuristic to find particularly damaging attacks in this regime.
We applied these weak regime techniques to determine the
effect of malicious data attacks on prices in electricity markets.
